caption: Our go to. We order soup 2 times a wk sometimes. Everything is pretty delicious and it’s a cute vibe to dine in as well!
Had some spring rolls , fried rice and chicken wings ! Not bad at all. Will come and check your further !
The more delicious food in town is here

Hey guys you got an Asian person's endorsement here! Try the Soup Dumplings for sure, it's delicious and very authentic! Here's a little tutorial of how to properly eat soup dumplings: Spend 1 minute watching how beautifully the broth jiggles in the dumplings skin, then take a little nibble on the side of the dumpling,  suck the flavorful broth out of the dumpling, then depends on your personal preference to dip it in the Chinese vinegar before eat the whole thing or just eat it straight without vinegar. I had a fun conversation with the owner today, felt so happy to find authentic shanghai soup dumplings in this neighborhood. it's RARE! Will def come back and try other dishes :)
Love this place too much
There was an error with my Seamless order and the restaurant took care of it immediately - above and beyond service and great food.

We have been ordering every Sunday night and tonight I had to write a review. Even with the snow and the cold, the food arrived so fast and super hot.  We love our Sunday routine with the mix vegetables plate & my boyfriend with the Hai Pai (plus spring rolls that are the best I ever had). I usually don’t write that many reviews but they deserve because of their consistency with a great food and time. You guys are amazing, best Chinese place!

Hands down, the very best Chinese food I've ever eaten in my entire life. The staff members are all incredible. Eat at the gem, you won't be disappointed.  Update: Wei's is still the best Chinese food ever. Their take out is somehow still absolutely perfect. I missed this restaurant so much during Covid.
Will never order from here again.

Honestly nothing special. We got General Tso Chicken, Sesame Chicken, and BBQ Pork Buns. The first two were soggy, and the bbq pork buns didn't have any salt or sugar. I didn't know you could get bbq pork buns wrong...

This is a quiet little place decorated with many red paper lanterns. They play funky music and have cozy seating. I sat in one of the corner booths which was very comfortable. I had an 88 martini, which was like a Manhattan with Chinese wine. Yums😋 To eat, I ordered the vege hot and sour soup, vege spring rolls, vege dumplings, and mu shu shrimp. Everything was very tasty. The spring rolls were particularly good with a perfect crispy outside. It's some of the best Chinese food in the area.
Super nice atmosphere and the food is fresh and delicious. Will come again soon!

This is maybe my favorite place in nyc. Ok, so the drinks are epic, not expensive and strong. Take the Shanghai Cowboy. The vibe is perfect. It's like you're out in the most chill and relaxed way. The owner and all crew members are super nice, I still miss Aaron. The food is also great. I LOVE the veggie dumplings and really the ration btw $ and what you get is unbeatable. If you're there very likely I'm there too. Even the fiancée says It's the DREAM.

The food is decently tasty, but I think wei’s needs to up the game on their ingredients - the chicken is usually quite gristly and has an unappealing texture. Feels like what you’d expect from a $5 plate of food rather than the tier of restaurants Wei’s is placed in.

This is so sad and disappointing. Ordered veg lo mein, tofu kung pao, scallion pancakes, Chinese broccoli, spring rolls. Every single thing was greasy and completely flavorless. Scallion pancake had about 5 scallions in it, was just a translucent greasy fried wonton. The Chinese broccoli was just steamed with no garlic or seasoning of any kind, the only non greasy thing. The noodles were greasy and flavorless... this food was really very bad all around, and $50. Im not even that picky. I was really looking forward to this meal after a long day at work, and was looking forward to trying this place after hearing so many good things since we live just around the corner.
Excellent food and service!

Rain, storm, late ungodly hours or COVID19, this place came through when I was craving something. Their spicy wontons are delicious, with a delicious pork filling, and their shrimp dumplings are light, fresh, and a delicious small bite. I'd drive any day to this place for my Chinese food cravings!

The BEST. Great vibes, food, and people. Can’t wait until we can dine in again because you can’t beat the ambiance. The good news is when you order take out you can eat your soup dumplings (almost) right away without burning your mouth off. The salt and pepper shrimp is underrated. Try it! Never had a bad dish here and I’m sure I never well. I have brought my entire family and all my visitors here and everyone is obsessed. Love Wei’s and everything about it!

Consistently delicious food very convenient to drop in, never had to wait for a table. Decently priced and good music ! A little vibe in there. Staff is attentive not overly friendly and not rude. So a good mix! Very prompt service.

Thoroughly enjoyed the entire experience.  I have never once enjoyed tofu, but somehow Wei made some so delectable I ate almost all of our shared serving.  Thank you for a memorable and amazing experience and my wife and I will return soon!

One of the best chinese spots in Williamsburg. The ambiance here is cool and groovy with a DJ spinning music on Tuesday nights. The food here is great. I'd recommend trying to Wei's spicy chicken. Great flavor and not that spicy. Also, the pork and chive dumplings are a good starter option.

Love Wei's! This is out new favourite after work spot, my coworkers and I are absolutely obsessed. We've been working our way through everything on the menu and never had a single meal that wasn't absolutely delicious. Great prices (for such high quality food) and the drinks are delicious too. The staff are super cute and lovely, the service is so fast, and the whole vibe of the place is just great. Legit my fave place in the neighbourhood

Pricier than other Chinese restos in the area, but they give generous servings and you won’t get that MSG hangover the next day haha. Notable dishes are the xiao long bao, ribs, and chicken. Like that this place also closes late. Nice to go here after a night of partying.

Many of my friends have been coming here a lot, saying this is a great place to dine out for the night. I decided to try it out for myself to see if it was worth the hype. A couple days ago, I visited Wei’s Williamsburg and ordered the sautéed bok choy with mushrooms. The mushrooms in the dish were sour and seemed as if it was left there for days. I also ordered the chicken broccoli dish. The portions and serving size was very small and it was barely enough to fill just myself. The chicken was also not fresh. When I left that night, my stomach felt very uncomfortable. Never coming back. Do your research before you go. All these 5 star reviews are falsely advertised!! Incredibly disappointed with my experience here.

Stumbled upon this place late one night a few years ago. It is the absolute BEST food around! Whether it’s a date, a late night, take out, or just wanting to grab a drink, this place is my Go-To!!!! The owner Wei is always there and makes you feel at home. Such an amazing hard working man and team! Truly my favorite restaurant in all of NYC and Brooklyn! Thanks for everything Wei! See you soon!

Have been living in the States for almost 7 years, I honestly don't quite remember how Chinese food is supposed to be, or even worst, I am not sure what is Chinese food anymore. With that been said, I think Wei's food are as good as Chinese food is to me.  We order Crispy Ducks, Mofo tofu, veggie Wotan soup and some rice.  No, we didn't not order General Tso's chicken. Sorry white people, I know that is your favorite Chinese food, but it is not Chinese food.  I assume Hai Pai chicken is Shanghai style chicken, but there is no Shanghai style chicken, so I was confused. Actually the menu is confusing in general like most American Chinese restaurants. So we only ordered what we know for sure. Can't take the risk when we craving food from home.

After seeing a post about Wei’s on IG, I knew I had to go. I’m a huge fan of dumplings so naturally this place was calling my name. Yesterday I finally checked it out with several friends (two who frequent Wei’s often) and enjoyed a few shared plates. We ordered soup dumplings (highly recommend!), garlic green beans (again, highly recommend!), spicy veggie wontons with chili oil (these weren’t spicy and for some reason had a strong taste of peanuts) and Wei’s Spicy Chicken which wasn’t spicy either. The food was good but what really made the experience was the ambience - a DJ was spinning at the end of the bar which created a super cool late night vibe as we dined. I’d come back.

Wei's is a great place to eat that doesn't require a lot of thinking, similar to the convenience of picking fresh food off a dim sum cart. The space is cozy and a server was always within sight and always available. Our food came out very fast. Probably because they keep the food steaming in the back. Our server's name was Aaron. As a server myself, I have to say that I was very impressed with Aaron's service. Thanks so much for the great meal!
